---
/**
 * topology.astro — The deployment picture, in one diagram and four sections.
 *
 * Audience: a reader who has seen the four pillars and the API reference
 * but isn't sure where the broker runs, where the worker runs, where
 * NemoClaw fits, and what "the attested boundary" actually covers.
 *
 * This page exists because the terms "the broker," "the worker," "the
 * NemoClaw instance," and "the enclave" are used interchangeably in
 * marketing copy, and they're not the same thing. Concretely:
 *
 *   - The broker daemon is a Python process on a t3.small, installed as
 *     a bare systemd service by scripts/bootstrap-control-plane.sh. It
 *     is NOT running inside NemoClaw.
 *   - The worker is a separate EC2 instance (m6a.xlarge, AMD SEV-SNP).
 *     One worker per region by default; scale via warm pool.
 *   - The NemoClaw *sandbox* (the thing the user means when they say
 *     "NemoClaw instance") is a process inside the worker EC2, spawned
 *     by `nemohermes exec` for each LLM skill. It shares the worker's
 *     SEV-SNP attestation — it is not separately attested.
 *   - The SEV-SNP attestation covers the whole worker EC2, including
 *     any NemoClaw sub-sandboxes spawned inside it.
 *
 * Source-code references are accurate as of 2026-06-30.
 */
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteNav    from '~/components/SiteNav.astro';
import Footer     from '~/components/Footer.astro';

const diagram = `\
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ AWS account (eu-west-1)                                             │
│                                                                     │
│ ┌────────────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────────────────────┐   │
│ │ Broker daemon          │    │ Worker EC2 (m6a.xlarge)         │   │
│ │ Python, always-on      │    │ AMD SEV-SNP + remote attest.    │   │
│ │ t3.small               │    │                                 │   │
│ │ systemd service        │    │  ┌────────────────────────────┐ │   │
│ │ (NOT in NemoClaw)      │    │  │ worker/poller.py           │ │   │
│ │                        │    │  │                            │ │   │
│ │  ┌──────────────────┐  │    │  │  runs the skill:           │ │   │
│ │  │ /v1/discover     │  │    │  │                            │ │   │
│ │  │ /v1/jobs         │  │◀──▶│  │  WASM ─▶ wasmtime         │ │   │
│ │  │ /v1/llm proxy ─────────────────▶  or                    │ │   │
│ │  │ Stripe lifecycle │  │    │  │  LLM ─▶ nemohermes exec ──────▶┌───────────────────────────┐ │
│ │  └──────────────────┘  │    │  │            │            │ │   │ NemoClaw sandbox         │ │
│ │                        │    │  │ ───────────│────────────│─┼──▶│ (process inside the      │ │
│ │  EFS share ◀───────────│────│─▶│ ──── heartbeat ────▶   │ │   │  worker EC2, NOT a new   │ │
│ │  (envelope, logs,      │    │  └────────────────────────────┘ │   │  instance)              │ │
│ │   worker keys)         │    │           │              │   │   │                           │ │
│ └────────────────────────┘    │           │              │   │   │  OpenShell policy:        │ │
│           │                   │           ▼              ▼   │   │   egress = broker IP only │ │
│           │                   │  sev_snp.py            S3 KMS│   │                           │ │
│           ▼                   │  ↓                     ↓     │   │  LLM call ─▶ broker proxy │ │
│     ┌──────────┐               │  1184-byte SNP report │      │   │           ▲               │ │
│     │  Stripe  │               │  cert chain           │      │   │           │               │ │
│     │  Payment │               │  chip_id              │      │   └───────────┼───────────────┘ │
│     │  Intent  │               │  worker_binding HMAC  │      │               │                 │
│     └──────────┘               │                       │      │   inherits worker attestation   │
│                                │ attested ──▶ /v1/discover  │   │ (same enclave, same report)   │
│                                └─────────────────────────────────┘                           │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\
`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Topology — Where the broker runs, where the worker runs, where NemoClaw fits"
  description="The deployment picture in one diagram and four sections. The broker daemon is a Python process on a t3.small; the worker is a separate EC2 (m6a.xlarge, AMD SEV-SNP); the NemoClaw instance is a process inside the worker EC2, not a new instance. SEV-SNP attestation covers the whole worker EC2."
>
  <SiteNav />
  <main class="bg-bg text-ink">
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="vf-container pt-30 pb-16">
      <p class="vf-eyebrow text-verdigris-deep">Architecture</p>
      <h1 class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        Where the broker runs. Where the worker runs. Where NemoClaw fits.
      </h1>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-8 max-w-3xl">
        Four things get called "the enclave" in different parts of the
        docs. They are not the same. This page is the picture, drawn once,
        with the four sections underneath explaining each layer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- The diagram -->
    <section class="vf-container section-sm" aria-labelledby="diagram-heading">
      <h2 id="diagram-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl sr-only">
        Topology diagram
      </h2>
      <pre class="vf-code mt-8 max-w-4xl overflow-x-auto text-caption leading-tight"><code>{diagram}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <!-- 1. Broker -->
    <section class="vf-container section" aria-labelledby="broker-heading">
      <h2 id="broker-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        1. The broker — always-on control plane, not in NemoClaw.
      </h2>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        The broker is the Python daemon that holds the queue, the Stripe
        payment lifecycle, the per-job LLM tokens, and the LLM proxy. It is
        cheap (a <code class="font-mono">t3.small</code> in eu-west-1) and
        always-on. It is <strong>not</strong> running inside NemoClaw —
        <code class="font-mono">scripts/bootstrap-control-plane.sh</code>
        installs it as a bare <code class="font-mono">systemd</code> service
        on the host. NemoClaw only appears at the worker side (see
        <a href="#nemoclaw-heading" class="vf-link">section 3</a>).
      </p>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        It exposes the public API:
      </p>
      <ul class="text-body mt-6 max-w-3xl space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
        <li><code class="font-mono text-copper">GET  /v1/discover</code> — attestation block, pricing, supported skills</li>
        <li><code class="font-mono text-copper">POST /v1/jobs</code> — submit a job (encrypted payload + Stripe PI)</li>
        <li><code class="font-mono text-copper">GET  /v1/jobs/&#123;id&#125;</code> — poll; once completed, returns encrypted result + signatures</li>
        <li><code class="font-mono text-copper">POST /v1/llm/chat/completions</code> — the LLM proxy used by worker sandboxes</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. Worker -->
    <section class="vf-container section" aria-labelledby="worker-heading">
      <h2 id="worker-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        2. The worker — separate EC2, AMD SEV-SNP, launched on demand.
      </h2>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        The worker is a separate EC2 instance (<code class="font-mono">m6a.xlarge</code>,
        AMD SEV-SNP enabled) that runs the actual workload. The broker
        launches it on demand via <code class="font-mono">scripts/warm-worker-manager.sh</code>
        and holds it in a warm pool so jobs don't pay the ~16-minute
        cold-start cost on every submission.
      </p>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        One worker = one SEV-SNP attestation report. The report covers
        the entire EC2: kernel, init system, poller process, every child
        process, and any NemoClaw sandbox spawned inside it. This is the
        single hardware-attested boundary. <strong>If you want to know
        what's running, the worker's attestation report is what you
        verify.</strong>
      </p>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        The worker has two execution paths:
      </p>
      <ul class="text-body mt-6 max-w-3xl space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
        <li>
          <strong>WASM skill:</strong> runs directly on the worker host
          via <code class="font-mono">wasmtime</code> with manifest-declared
          fuel + duration caps. No sandbox layer — the wasmtime engine is
          the sandbox.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>LLM skill:</strong> runs inside a NemoClaw sandbox
          spawned by <code class="font-mono">nemohermes exec</code>
          (<code class="font-mono">worker/poller.py:1028 dispatch_to_sandbox</code>).
          The LLM call inside the sandbox is intercepted by the
          OpenShell policy and forwarded to the broker's LLM proxy over
          HTTP — the real LLM API key never enters the worker.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- 3. NemoClaw -->
    <section class="vf-container section" aria-labelledby="nemoclaw-heading">
      <h2 id="nemoclaw-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        3. The NemoClaw sandbox — process inside the worker, not a new instance.
      </h2>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        This is the part that confused you (and a lot of reviewers). When
        the marketing copy says "the NemoClaw instance," it usually means
        <strong>one NemoClaw sandbox</strong> — a child process inside the
        worker EC2, started by <code class="font-mono">nemohermes exec</code>
        when the worker dispatches an LLM skill. It is not a new EC2, not
        a new VM, not a new hardware attestation boundary. It is one
        process running under an OpenShell policy, inside the attested
        worker.
      </p>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        One NemoClaw sandbox per LLM job. The sandbox:
      </p>
      <ul class="text-body mt-6 max-w-3xl space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
        <li>Inherits the worker EC2's SEV-SNP attestation (same enclave, same report).</li>
        <li>Has its own <code class="font-mono">inference.local</code> OpenShell policy that blocks all egress except to the broker's LLM proxy IP.</li>
        <li>Receives a per-job <code class="font-mono">llm_token</code> as its <code class="font-mono">COMPATIBLE_API_KEY</code> (10-min TTL, one-shot).</li>
        <li>Runs the skill's <code class="font-mono">prompt_template</code> with the decrypted input data.</li>
        <li>Has its own wall-clock cap (<code class="font-mono">WORKER_SANDBOX_INNER_TIMEOUT_S=120</code>) and dispatch timeout (<code class="font-mono">WORKER_SANDBOX_DISPATCH_TIMEOUT_S=180</code>).</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        If the NemoClaw installer is missing on the worker (which happens
        on fresh AMIs before the bootstrap runs), the worker falls back
        to a legacy host-direct LLM call to the broker proxy. Same
        network policy enforced by OpenShell once installed; looser
        (kernel-level) before installation.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 vf-card border-copper/40 max-w-3xl">
        <p class="vf-eyebrow text-copper-deep">What the current sandbox attestation looks like</p>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          Today, the result envelope includes a <code class="font-mono">sandbox</code> block
          (see <code class="font-mono">worker/poller.py:2611</code>) with
          four fields:
        </p>
        <pre class="vf-code mt-4 max-w-prose-vf"><code>{`{
  "name":               "<sandbox name from nemohermes>",
  "attested":           true | false,
  "network_policy":     "openshell-enforced",
  "inference_route":    "inference.local -> broker proxy http://<ip>:8080/v1/llm",
  "error":              "<only present if attested=false>"
}`}</code></pre>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          This proves the sandbox ran with the right egress policy, but it
          does <strong>not</strong> pin the NemoClaw version, the sandbox
          image hash, or sign anything. A reviewer can verify the network
          surface but cannot verify which version of NemoClaw actually ran.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 vf-card border-verdigris/40 max-w-3xl">
        <p class="vf-eyebrow text-verdigris-deep">Shipping now — worker signs the NemoClaw image digest (Plan 2)</p>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          Worker-side change: after <code class="font-mono">nemohermes onboard</code>,
          the worker captures <code class="font-mono">nemoclaw_version</code>,
          the Docker image name, and the image digest. It signs the bundle
          with its Ed25519 key (already bound to the SEV-SNP report via
          <code class="font-mono">worker_binding</code>) and includes the
          signature in the result envelope. Reviewer-side check is the new
          <a href="/verify-attestation/#step-6" class="vf-link">Step 6 of /verify-attestation</a>.
        </p>
        <pre class="vf-code mt-4 max-w-prose-vf"><code>{`{
  "name":                "<sandbox name from nemohermes>",
  "attested":            true | false,
  "network_policy":      "openshell-enforced",
  "inference_route":     "inference.local -> broker proxy http://<ip>:8080/v1/llm",
  "nemoclaw_version":    "0.7.2",
  "nemoclaw_image":      "nemoclaw/nemoclaw:0.7.2",
  "nemoclaw_image_digest": "sha256:abc123...",
  "image_digest_sig":    "<worker Ed25519 sig over (version|digest|name|pubkey|report_data[:128])>",
  "error":               "<only present if attested=false>"
}`}</code></pre>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          The signature is verifiable end-to-end. Walking the chain:
        </p>
        <pre class="vf-code mt-2 max-w-prose-vf"><code>{`image_digest_sig
  → worker Ed25519 key  (published in worker-keys.json)
    → worker X25519 pubkey  (also in worker-keys.json)
      → worker_binding HMAC  (in report_data, signed by AMD chip)
        → SEV-SNP report  (signed by AMD chip)
          → VLEK/VCEK cert chain
            → AMD ARK root  (pinned in verifier environment)`}</code></pre>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          What this catches: worker pulling a different NemoClaw image than
          the requester expected; MITM on the nemohermes download. What it
          does not catch: operator shipping a custom NemoClaw build and
          calling it "v0.7.2." That residual trust is unavoidable until
          NemoClaw ships a signed image manifest.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 vf-card border-bg/40 max-w-3xl">
        <p class="vf-eyebrow text-bg-soft">Future work — Option 2: bake NemoClaw into the AMI</p>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          Today, <code class="font-mono">nemohermes</code> downloads the
          NemoClaw Docker image at runtime from NVIDIA's CDN. The image
          lands in the worker's filesystem <strong>after</strong> the
          SEV-SNP launch measurement is taken, so the chip never sees it.
          The worker-side signing in "Shipping now" above catches the
          worker pulling a different image, but doesn't hardware-attest
          the image itself.
        </p>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          To hardware-attest the image, the operator would:
        </p>
        <ol class="text-body mt-2 max-w-prose-vf space-y-2 list-decimal pl-6">
          <li>
            Modify the AMI build pipeline (Packer) to download the
            NemoClaw Docker image at AMI build time, extract it into
            <code class="font-mono">/var/lib/docker</code> (so it's part of
            the AMI's filesystem, not a runtime fetch), and capture the
            resulting image digest.
          </li>
          <li>
            Publish a <code class="font-mono">min_measurement</code> table
            per (NemoClaw version, AMI id) the same way the existing
            <code class="font-mono">min_measurement</code> is published.
          </li>
          <li>
            The requester compares the published
            <code class="font-mono">min_measurement</code> against the
            chip's report for any live worker. The SEV-SNP signature on
            the report <em>is</em> the signature on the AMI, including
            the embedded NemoClaw image.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          <strong>Trade-offs:</strong> larger AMIs (NemoClaw image is
          ~1–2 GB baked in), AMI rebuilds every NemoClaw version bump,
          and reproducible AMI builds are hard (NemoClaw is a moving
          target). But it eliminates the ~16-min cold start, closes the
          runtime-fetch trust gap, and gives hardware-attested version
          pinning — no more trusting the operator's
          <code class="font-mono">worker-keys.json</code> claims.
        </p>
        <p class="vf-body-lead mt-4">
          This is out of scope for the current deploy (it requires an
          operator-side AMI build change and a NemoClaw build-step
          cooperation). Plan 1 (Shipping now) is the right answer for
          the current threat model; Option 2 is the right answer for a
          deployment where the operator wants hardware-attested version
          pinning.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4. What's the attested boundary? -->
    <section class="vf-container section" aria-labelledby="boundary-heading">
      <h2 id="boundary-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        4. The attested boundary — what the SEV-SNP report covers.
      </h2>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-6 max-w-3xl">
        The single attestation report at <code class="font-mono">/v1/discover</code>
        covers the whole worker EC2. Concretely:
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-8">
        <table class="vf-table max-w-4xl">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th class="text-left">Layer</th>
              <th class="text-left">In the attestation report?</th>
              <th class="text-left">What stops it from being tampered with</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-body-sm">
            <tr>
              <td>Worker EC2 kernel + init</td>
              <td>Yes (part of <code class="font-mono">measurement</code>)</td>
              <td>SEV-SNP memory encryption + AMD chip signature</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code class="font-mono">worker/poller.py</code></td>
              <td>Yes (part of <code class="font-mono">measurement</code>)</td>
              <td>Same</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code class="font-mono">wasmtime</code> + WASM skill</td>
              <td>Yes (part of <code class="font-mono">measurement</code>)</td>
              <td>Same</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>NemoClaw sandbox (LLM skill)</td>
              <td>Yes (process inside the attested enclave)</td>
              <td>SEV-SNP memory isolation; OpenShell policy blocks egress</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>OpenShell policy file</td>
              <td>Indirectly (its SHA-256 is in <code class="font-mono">policy_hash</code>, bound via <code class="font-mono">worker_binding</code>)</td>
              <td>If the policy changes, the binding HMAC changes, the report becomes invalid</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Worker X25519 keypair</td>
              <td>Indirectly (the pubkey is in <code class="font-mono">report_data</code>, HMAC-bound to policy_hash)</td>
              <td>Same — key swap breaks the binding</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="vf-body-lead mt-8 max-w-3xl">
        So when you read <code class="font-mono">/v1/discover</code> and
        verify the five checks on <a href="/verify-attestation/" class="vf-link">/verify-attestation</a>,
        you are verifying <strong>everything that runs in the worker</strong>:
        the WASM engine, the poller, the NemoClaw sandbox process, and
        the OpenShell policy that constrains it. There is no separate
        attestation for "the NemoClaw instance" because there is no
        separate instance — it's a process inside the attested EC2.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Key takeaways -->
    <section class="vf-container section" aria-labelledby="takeaways-heading">
      <h2 id="takeaways-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        Key takeaways.
      </h2>
      <ul class="text-body mt-6 max-w-3xl space-y-3 list-disc pl-6">
        <li>
          <strong>EC2 count:</strong> 1 broker (always on) + 1+ workers (warm pool).
          Not "1 AWS instance running multiple NemoClaw instances."
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>NemoClaw appears in two places:</strong> the broker
          control-plane sandbox (deployment-time) and the per-LLM-job
          sandbox inside the worker (execution-time). They share a name,
          not a process boundary.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>One attestation report covers one worker EC2.</strong>
          The report doesn't enumerate child processes — it attests the
          initial VM memory contents, and everything that runs inside
          inherits that trust.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>"NemoClaw instance" = NemoClaw sandbox process</strong>
          inside the worker. One per LLM job, terminated when the job
          ends, no separate hardware boundary.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Network policy is what isolates NemoClaw from the
          outside world</strong> — OpenShell default-DENY + a strict
          allowlist of broker IPs. The SEV-SNP attestation is what binds
          that policy to the running worker (via <code class="font-mono">worker_binding</code>).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Where to go next -->
    <section class="vf-container section-sm" aria-labelledby="next-heading">
      <h2 id="next-heading" class="vf-heading-section mt-6 max-w-4xl">
        Where to go from here.
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-12 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 max-w-5xl">
        <a href="/verify-attestation/" class="vf-card hover:border-copper">
          <p class="vf-eyebrow text-copper-deep">Now that you have the picture</p>
          <p class="font-display font-semibold text-ink mt-3 text-display-sm">Verify the attestation</p>
          <p class="text-body-sm text-ink-soft mt-4">
            Five concrete checks against <code class="font-mono text-caption">GET /v1/discover</code> — decode the 1184-byte report, walk the cert chain to AMD's ARK, verify the worker_binding HMAC.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a href="/attestation/" class="vf-card hover:border-copper">
          <p class="vf-eyebrow text-copper-deep">Background</p>
          <p class="font-display font-semibold text-ink mt-3 text-display-sm">What is attestation?</p>
          <p class="text-body-sm text-ink-soft mt-4">
            The pillar deep dive — the three-step handshake, the
            attack/defense matrix, and what each check actually proves.
          </p>
        </a>
        <a href="/agents/" class="vf-card hover:border-copper">
          <p class="vf-eyebrow text-copper-deep">Operator setup</p>
          <p class="font-display font-semibold text-ink mt-3 text-display-sm">Run your own broker</p>
          <p class="text-body-sm text-ink-soft mt-4">
            <code class="font-mono text-caption">bootstrap-control-plane.sh</code>,
            <code class="font-mono text-caption">warm-worker-manager.sh</code>,
            the OpenShell policy file, the Stripe wiring.
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>